Let $w = z^2.$  Then
\[w^4 - w^3 + w^2 - w + 1 = 0.\]We can factor this as
\[(w^2 + 1)(w^2 - w + 1) = 0.\]The quadratic $w^2 + 1 = 0$ has roots $w = \pm i.$  The quadratic $w^2 - w + 1 = 0$ has roots
\[w = \frac{1 \pm i \sqrt{3}}{2}.\]Hence, the roots of $z^8 - z^6 + z^4 - z^2 + 1 = 0$ are
\[z = \pm \sqrt{i}, \quad z = \pm \sqrt{\frac{1 + i \sqrt{3}}{2}}, \quad z = \pm \sqrt{\frac{1 - i \sqrt{3}}{2}}.\]We can write
\[\sqrt{i} = \sqrt{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} i} = \sqrt{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}} \cdot \sqrt{1 + i} = \sqrt{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}} \cdot \left( \frac{\sqrt{2 + 2 \sqrt{2}}}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{2 - 2 \sqrt{2}}}{2} i \right).\]Then
\[\operatorname{Im} \sqrt{i} = \sqrt{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2 - 2 \sqrt{2}}}{2} = \frac{\sqrt{1 - \sqrt{2}}}{2}.\]Similarly,
\begin{align*}
\operatorname{Im} \sqrt{\frac{1 + i \sqrt{3}}{2}} &= \operatorname{Im} \left( \sqrt{\frac{\sqrt{1^2 + (\sqrt{3})^2}}{2}} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{1}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i} \right) \\
&= \operatorname{Im} \left( \sqrt{\frac{\sqrt{1^2 + (\sqrt{3})^2}}{2}} \cdot \left( \frac{\sqrt{2 + \sqrt{12}}}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{2 - \sqrt{12}}}{2} i \right) \right) \\
&= \frac{\sqrt{2 - \sqrt{12}}}{2} \\
&= \frac{\sqrt{2 - 2 \sqrt{3}}}{2} \\
&= \frac{\sqrt{3} - 1}{2}.
\end{align*}The other roots have imaginary parts which are the negatives of these, so the maximum imaginary part is $\frac{\sqrt{3} - 1}{2}.$

